:: Fossil fuel companies will decarbonise [footer] {"position":"750,1425","size":"100,100"}
It would be nice if this were really true, but we cannot rely on the private sector to decarbonise at the rate we need - even the Financial Times says that "Capitalism won‚Äôt deliver the energy transition fast enough"<sup>1</sup>. The financial returns from renewables are so much lower than fossil fuels, because once you‚Äôve set up the site, then the fuel that powers the generation (wind and sun) is literally free. Fossil fuels (and nuclear/hydrogen) cost far more to run because you‚Äôre constantly paying for more fuel.

Governments literally have to guarantee prices far higher for renewables than they would actually cost to run, to make it worth the while for private companies to decide to bid for renewable energy contracts (and if set the maximum bids too low, this has resulted in no private companies wanting to make offers<sup>2</sup>). A public energy provider would not have to make a profit - its only goal would be to make sure the UK meets its decarbonisation goals and provides cheaper energy.

Let's try something different.


