:: Windfall tax on the energy providers {"position":"700,875","size":"100,100"}
It's tempting to go for an approach like this, but it's not necessarily one that materially helps anyone. 

Yes this reduces the energy providers' profits, and also has the effect of reducing the amount of money they can redistribute to their shareholders, but nothing will change regarding the soaring amounts of money that people have to pay for their energy. And ultimately the companies may just pass on higher costs to their customers.

Finally as we know from Modern Monetary Theory, taxes don‚Äôt subsequently fund spending, so all that will happen is that this money will disappear from circulation.

